@flexiarg writing-coherence/balanced-pair-padding
@title Lead With the Real Claim; Strawmen Appear Only If a Reader Would
@keywords balanced-pair, not-x-but-y, strawman, rhetorical-padding, false-choice
@audience paper authors, reviewers
@tone technical
@style pattern
@references [writing-coherence/triad-inflation]

! conclusion: The construction "not X, but also not Y; rather Z" frequently hides the fact that Z is doing all the argumentative work while X and Y are strawmen no reader would actually have proposed.  The balanced pair lends Z the appearance of hard-won middle ground.  Lead with Z; introduce X and Y only when a reader plausibly would have raised them.
  + context: AI prose loves the balanced pair.  The construction is rhetorically soothing — it signals consideration, nuance, dialectical thinking — even when the X and Y positions exist only in the paragraph that rejects them.  When Z stands up on its own, the pair is padding.  When Z would be misread without the pair, the pair is earning its keep.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: rhetorical setup ↔ argumentative economy.
    Real: a genuine dialectical move clarifies what a position is by showing what it rejects.  A synthetic dialectical move gives the position unearned weight by inventing rejections.
    Irreducible: the same construction cannot simultaneously be (a) necessary dialectical framing and (b) padding.  It is one or the other for any given use.
    Active: the pull recurs at every claim the writer is not sure will land on its own.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Lead with Z: state the claim directly.  If the reader accepts it without confusion, X and Y were unnecessary.
    (2) Reintroduce the pair only for a live misreading: if a reader plausibly would have taken Z to mean X or Y, introduce X or Y as the specific misreading being ruled out, not as generic alternatives.
    (3) Cut Z: occasionally the discovery is that Z is itself unclear.  The balanced pair was doing work Z should be doing.  Rewrite Z.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: every "not X, but Y" construction in the draft survives the question "would a reader actually have proposed X?"  Failing when: X is a position no competent reader of the paper would have held.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Strawman X: the rejected position is one the paper's own argument makes implausible.
    - Abstracted poles: X and Y are maximally abstract opposites ("not purely technical, not purely social") framing a Z that could be stated directly.
    - Triangulated comfort: the balanced pair appears in every paragraph, regardless of whether Z needs dialectical setup.
